    	<h2><a name="2003-03-02" href="#2003-03-02"><font color="#660000">2003-03-02</font></a></h2>
   	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="90012365">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<h1>Cyberspace</h1><h2>Orbital Junk</h2><h3>Dealing with Spam</h3>I'm one of those people who believe that Spam must be dealt with at the edges.&nbsp; There is no easy way to provide a gateway filter that satisifes all requirements or that won't be subverted more quickly than it can be updated.&nbsp; There must be a way to move it to the leaves and to take the profit incentive out of it for spammers.&nbsp; Meanwhile, this does make on-line-only e-mail services more difficult to deal with, unless they open up APIs or other avenues for controlled access by the recipient.<br /><br /><a href="http://www.wired.com/news/print/0,1294,57868,00.html">Wired News: Net Gurus Rally Anti-Spam Forces</a>.&nbsp; The Internet Research Task Force (a companion of the IETF) has launched an Anti-Spam Research Group.  It will meet for the first time at March's IETF meeting in San Francisco.&nbsp; I think this is promising.&nbsp; I don't expect any kind of centralized or hosted solution, but an edge solution.&nbsp; This article suggests that there is going to be emphasis on consent-based processes.&nbsp; That is intriguing.<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#90012365">Sunday, March 02, 2003</a></span></div>
